<br>
Possessions (2):<br>
2x The Palantir of Orthanc<br>
<br>
Conditions (6):<br>
2x <a href="javascript:card_browser(36)">Spies of Saruman</a><br>
2x Tower of Orthanc<br>
2x <a href="javascript:card_browser(949)">No Business of Ours</a><br>
<br>
Events (7):<br>
3x Abandoning Reason for Madness<br>
4x <a href="javascript:card_browser(855)">Savagery to Match Their Numbers</a>    </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Strategy</Font></TD><TD> </TD></TR><TR><TD COLSPAN="2" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="bfont"> STRATEGY<br>
This deck can win with either its fellowship or its shadow side, although the shadow side is primarily intended to slow the opponent down enough for me to race past them for the win at the end.  I usually bid zero, as most people bid to go first and I prefer to go second so I have Hollin, although going first isnt a problem either, as it guarantees me a first-turn Aragorn and gives me an early lead, making my Uruks that much more effective (since my opponent will either be forced to double-move to keep up, and my Uruks will bring the pain, or will choose to single-move, allowing me to keep my lead with easy single-moves).<br>
FELLOWSHIP<br>
The deck starts Gandalf TGP, but his only purpose in this deck is as a card-drawing engine and a support character who allows me to play Servant of the Secret Fire and Betrayal of Isengard.  The main focus of the deck is to make Aragorn and Boromir fighting machines capable of destroying virtually anything they face; the only minions they cant beat without Servants are the Cave Troll, the Balrog, Lurtz, Troop of Uruk-Hai, and the Witch-King.  However, Armor makes all of these minions insignificant; at worst, they do 2 wounds after the fierce fight, and at best I play a Servant and win the fight.  Even though these are the only minions that can defeat Boromir and Aragorn without strength boosters such as Savagery to Match Their Numbers, I like having them played against me, as their high cost usually means that they were played in place of at least 2 other minions.<br>
MATCHUPS<br>
-Nazgul:  The only way Nazgul can hurt this deck is if you play foolishly or if they get Black Breaths and Blade Tips on all of your companions early (and even this can be dealt with; Elrond shows up with his ring and bounces the conditions back to their hand like nobodys business, and they either get discarded or they clog the opponents hand).  When I say Nazgul can hurt if the deck is played foolishly, I mean things like giving Aragorn his bow if you dont know for a fact that your opponent isnt playing They Will Never Stop Hunting You and Relentless Charge.  Against Nazgul, DISCARD THE BOW.  I know its nice, but you should never be shooting down Nazgul in this deck.  It takes a minimum of 3 exertions to kill a Nazgul, and no Nazgul should ever do more than 2 wounds to you (and most of them cant even win skirmishes against Aragorn and Boromir).  Twilight Nazgul/Nazgul Corruption are an even easier matchup, as they rely on their Nazgul winning skirmishes to be effective, and against this deck it doesnt happen often.<br>
-Uruks:  Uruks are not the best matchup for this deck, but Aragorn and Boromir can beat most of them in skirmishes (all of them, with Servants), Armor takes care of the ones you cant beat, and if something really bad shows up (such as Saruman accompanying Lurtz with his sword, 4 Ambitions in the support area, and some Savageries and Battle Cries in your opponents hand), you can always toss him on Gandalf and cancel the skirmish.<br>
-Isengard Orcs:  Congratulations, you win J.  OK, so its not that easy, but almost.  With Sting and Glamdring you should never be giving them enough twilight to drop a lot of guys, and the minions that they do play get severely beaten by Aragorn , Boromir, and Gandalf; all are potentially damage +1, so none of their minions should have enough free exertions for their abilities except Orc Commander (who has 1 free exertion to do a wound; just give it to Frodo), and even if they do manage to use their exertion abilities, you can heal enough wounds with KiE, Elrond, discarding copies of Aragorn and Boromir, and Athelas that it really doesnt matter.<br>
-Moria:  Moria can be tough if they get a really strong swarm quickly, but between 2x PATHS, 4x Servant, and 2x Aragorns Bow you really shouldnt have a problem, especially with Elrond sending annoying conditions like Goblin Swarms and They Are Coming back to their hand.<br>
-Sauron:  If theyre playing Sauron Pain (Hate, Orc Bowmen, Under the Watching Eye), your healing and condition removal should take care of anything they can throw at you.  Just be careful about keeping Elrond out of Tower Assassin range, and you should be fine; to even put a dent in their fellowship, theyll have to save up at least 3 Hates (to get your lowest-vitality companion, Boromir) and minions with enough exertions to use them, which will either not happen or will severely clog your opponents hand.  If theyre playing Sauron Overwhelm/power, dont worry about it, just keep your burdens low and hold Servants as backup.<br>
SHADOW<br>
While this shadow is intended primarily just to slow your opponent down, the Uruks can be used quite effectively as game-winners, as it doesnt take much for you to decimate an entire fellowship in a single turn.  Your minions are strong and dangerous enough to make an opponent very hesitant to double-move against you.  When youre playing shadow, its a win-win situation; either your opponent single-moves, allowing your fellowship to race ahead, or they double-move, allowing your Uruks to beat the fellowship bloody and often kill so many companions that Frodo soon finds himself all alone.  This particular deck is centered around getting out a decent number of strong minions every turn, with only a few strength-adders (4x Savagery) to provide timely boosts and to take care of large fellowships.  Saruman is great for making all your Uruks fierce and serving as protection against archery/Blade of Gondor/PATHS; having Saruman on the table effectively doubles the number of wounds your Uruks inflict and makes your Uruks significantly harder to kill.<br>
MATCHUPS<br>
-Big Fellowship:  Uruks deal with superfellowship decks better than any other culture; as strong as your Uruks are normally, they just get that much more effective when the opponent hits the 5-companion mark; +4 from Savagery is huge, especially when you play several at once.  Also, superfellowship decks add lots of twilight to the pool, and Uruks love big pools.  Big fellowships are very popular in my area (Id say its tied with Elf/Ranger archery as the #1 decktype here), and this deck handles them with ease.<br>
-Small Fellowship/Twilight Denial:  This is the toughest matchup, but still very beatable.  Abandoning Reason for Madness keeps the cards flowing, and you can only be choked for so long; once the opponent leaves Lothlorien, youll have enough twilight to play 2 or 3 minions at each site with no problem, and twilight denial decks tend to have problems dealing with several Uruks at once.  Besides, if your opponent is playing a denial deck, their fellowship probably wont be moving very quickly, so your fellowship should win it for you.<br>
-Elf/Ranger Archery:  With Saruman, Uruks destroy archery decks.  You either drop a couple Uruks and play Spies of Saruman, then proceed to tear apart their fellowship (now left very unprotected without archery to thin the opposition), or play a few Uruks and Saruman and let them exert all their companions to get the archery total high enough to get around Saruman, then drop a beatdown crew of Uruks with Spies of Saruman at the next site, with all their companions so wounded from exerting to add archery that they all die in a single skirmish.<br>
-Dwarves:  Well, if you face someone playing dwarves, you should be questioning the competence of that player (just kidding, but really, dwarves arent exactly the most viable of cultures at this point).  Uruks do very well against Dwarves, as Saruman will keep your minions alive when your opponent plays a ton of pump events to win skirmishes, and when your opponent runs short on strength-adders, your Uruks will tear the dwarves apart; its just too hard to keep dwarves winning their skirmishes site after site, especially against Uruks.  However, if your opponent is somehow managing to beat all your Uruks with a never-ending flow of pump events, just pass when its time to play minions after they move; either theyll double-move, in which case you drop a ton of Uruks at once and some get through to Frodo, or theyll decide to stop after one move, meaning you have slowed them down (whether or not you did any damage or even played any minions is irrelevant).<br>
-Gondor:  Again, a tough matchup.  Try to do as much damage as possible before they get Armor down, and once they do just try to ping away at them until their companions are exhausted and the armor doesnt matter.  If this isnt working, try the strategy suggested against incredibly strong dwarf decks; pass when they move the first time, then drop a ton of guys at once if they double-move.  Gondor decks have very strong companions, but not very many of them, so they can have a hard time handling lots of minions at once.<br>
-Hobbits:  Hobbits can be a frustrating matchup early-on, with all those Stealths and Intuitions flying around, but they can only be played so many times, and once they either run out of stealth events or pass site 5, the partys over.  Hobbits have lots of vitality and can heal well, but Uruks do too many wounds all at once for even the best of Hobbit Healing Circles to deal with.  Basically, Uruks eat Hobbits.  Enough said.<br>
<br>
Well, thats all Ive got for now, Ive played this deck in several tournaments, never finishing worse than 2nd place, so it definitely works.  However, theres always room for improvement, so any suggestions and/or comments are welcome and appreciated.  Thanks for looking.<br>
